  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This dataset, deposited on Dryad in 2024 by Julia Bebout (University of California San Diego) and Jeremy W. Fox (University of Calgary), provides the data and code underpinning a methodological investigation into whether coordinated distributed experiments in ecology reliably reduce heterogeneity in effect size. Within its first year, the dataset has been formally cited once \u2014 by the companion article published in <em>Oikos</em> \u2014 and has accumulated 38 views and 11 downloads, representing an early but coherent footprint consistent with newly published research.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset supports a study addressing a foundational assumption in macroecological research design: that coordinated distributed experiments (CDEs), which replicate standardized protocols across multiple sites, should reduce between-site variance in estimated effect sizes relative to uncoordinated multi-site studies. Bebout and Fox interrogate this assumption through pairwise comparisons and variance decomposition, drawing on methods spanning ecological statistics, spatial heterogeneity analysis, and sample size considerations. The research speaks directly to the growing reliance on large collaborative network experiments \u2014 such as nutrient addition or biodiversity manipulation trials conducted simultaneously at dozens of sites \u2014 as a strategy for improving generalizability in ecology.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The sole formal citation to date is the companion journal article in <em>Oikos</em>, which itself carries five citations, suggesting that the intellectual contribution is gaining traction even as the dataset itself remains in early circulation. This citation relationship is a self-referential but meaningful one: the dataset is the evidentiary foundation of the published finding, and the Crossref-registered data citation confirms that the scholarly record explicitly links the two. The companion Zenodo software deposit, from which this Dryad dataset is derived, provides the computational infrastructure for reproducing the analyses, creating a complete and traceable research compendium across two open repositories.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of stewardship, the dataset benefits from deposition on Dryad, a well-established open-access repository registered with re3data and serving the life sciences community with DOI-based persistent identification. The associated analysis code is archived separately on Zenodo, reflecting good practice in separating data from software while maintaining explicit linkage between the two. Both platforms provide open access, and the green open-access status of the associated article further ensures that the findings and their supporting evidence are available without barriers to the broader research community.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">While the dataset's download count and citation record are modest at this early stage, these figures are entirely typical for methodological data papers in ecology within the first year of publication. The conceptual scope \u2014 challenging a widely accepted rationale for collaborative experimental design \u2014 positions this work to attract attention from researchers involved in multi-site ecological networks, meta-analysts, and statisticians working on heterogeneity and variance estimation. As awareness of the <em>Oikos</em> article grows, downstream engagement with the underlying data and code can be expected to increase accordingly.</p>",
